## Context

Seventeenth run. Four new journal entries, four new tasks. Major theme: GPX4/ferroptosis as a new druggable and predictive pathway in CD.

### Journal entries created
- #1974: GPX4 as druggable target predicting postoperative CD recurrence (Verstockt et al., Gastroenterology 2026, PMID 41850538). Selenium supplementation restores GPX4 in mice. Validated in 3 cohorts (241 patients). Top-priority finding.
- #1976: Post-resection disease reprogression independent of preoperative phenotype (Ghoneim et al., IBD 2026, PMID 41851033) + GPX4 as molecular recurrence predictor. Montreal B-classification not predictive post-surgery.
- #1980: GPX4-dependent ferroptosis governs ILC2 homeostasis in colitis (Liu et al., Cell Mol Immunol 2026, PMID 41663525). IBD patient ILC2s show reduced GPX4. Connects ferroptosis to TL1A-ILC axis. Plus CD8+ T cell scRNA-seq heterogeneity review (Zhong et al., PMID 41860039).
- #1982: Anti-OSMR (vixarelimab) Phase 1c IBD trial tissue assay (Jha et al., PMID 41867146). Body composition predicts biologic failure (Guo et al., PMID 41838416). IL1R1 causal via SMR (Chen & Hua, FASEB J, PMID 41773807).

### Tasks created
- #1262 (research_director, P4): Incorporate GPX4/ferroptosis pathway + selenium into fibrosis drug screen
- #1263 (research_director, P3): Evaluate GPX4 as stricture risk feature; deprioritize Montreal B-classification
- #1264 (research_director, P3): Add OSM/OSMR pathway signatures to anti-TNF non-response features
- #1265 (data_curator, P3): Check Verstockt et al. GPX4 data availability (3 cohorts, 241 patients)

### Key highlights for next run
- Ferroptosis emerges as major cross-cutting theme: GPX4 loss in epithelium predicts CD recurrence (Verstockt, Gastroenterology), GPX4 loss in ILC2s exacerbates colitis (Liu, Cell Mol Immunol), ferroptosis-microbiota connection (Xu, Medicine). Five pro-fibrotic cell populations now cataloged: (1) TWIST1+FAP+ fibroblasts (#1343), (2) inflammatory fibroblast spatial modules (#1536), (3) IL1β+macrophage→AREG→PI16+ fibroblasts (#1696), (4) γδ T cells via IL-17A (#1701), plus ferroptotic epithelial cells driving barrier breakdown→fibrosis (Verstockt #1974).
- Post-resection Montreal B-classification NOT predictive (Ghoneim #1976). Molecular features (GPX4, genomic) needed for stricture risk prediction — validates our approach.
- OSM/OSMR pathway: Vixarelimab (anti-OSMRβ) in Phase 1c IBD trials. OSM is a known anti-TNF resistance pathway.
- IL1R1 causal via SMR (PMID 41773807) — independently validates IL1β axis in fibrosis (#1696).
- PALI-2108 (NCT07428096): Phase 1b expected March 2026. No publications yet as of March 23. Continue monitoring.
- DDW 2026: Abstract notifications April 7. Conference May 2-5 Chicago. Mine after April 7.
- TL1A: No new significant papers this run beyond Pan & Wang letter (PMID 41317879, no abstract). BCD-261 Phase 2 COMANDOR still recruiting.
- Metabolomics: No new papers beyond run 16 batch. Three independent datasets still supporting metabolomics-first strategy.
- IL-23: No new response prediction/biomarker papers. VIVID-2 OLE (#1701) from last run remains latest. Still no AFFIRM/GALAXI biopsy transcriptomics.
- NOD2: No new papers. Paneth cell review (PMID 41838175) mentions NOD2 but no novel findings.
- GEO datasets: GSE319270 (vitamin D multi-omics IBD, only 2 samples — low priority). GSE312420/312415 already flagged run 16.
- Prior monitoring items still pending: Washburn pediatric CD scRNA-seq (#930), Kong Nat Genet spatial data (#1064), SPARC IBD metabolomics (#1065), ARES-CD CDx genotype panel, STENOVA OLE (H2 2026), Xie/Li fibrosis data availability, anti-TNF biomarker papers (SEMA3B, serum proteomics, HLA-DQB1*03:01).
- S1P modulators: Both ozanimod and etrasimod Phase 3 TERMINATED for CD. Mechanism insufficient for transmural inflammation.
- Dual-targeted therapy: upadacitinib+vedolizumab (VICTRIVA Phase 3b), upadacitinib+ustekinumab (Phase 4) both recruiting.
- Next: PALI-2108 results monitoring, DDW 2026 abstract mining (after April 7), AFFIRM/GALAXI biopsy substudies, ferroptosis-fibrosis mechanistic papers, Verstockt data deposition check, new anti-fibrotic compounds.
